### 1. `/var/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-b14c4924-20260507T231026-9169c6ef/skills/ddx/bead-lifecycle/SKILL.md`

This is the bead-lifecycle skill definition for DDx. It provides guidance for assessing bead readiness across five modes:

- **READINESS MODE**: Evaluates whether a bead is tractable and actionable before claim/dispatch using eight readiness failure reasons (too_large, ambiguous_scope, missing_root_cause_or_current_state, missing_verification, missing_code_path_assertion, missing_dependency_or_parent, hidden_external_blocker, already_satisfied_candidate). Returns JSON with classification (ready/needs_refine/needs_split/needs_human/system_unready), tractability score, readiness_checks array, suggested_fixes, and suggested_child_beads.

- **LINT MODE**: Scores beads against an 8-criterion rubric (title clarity, description completeness, AC verification naming, code-path assertions, test commands, labels, parent/deps explicitness, sufficient-prompt quality). Returns JSON score (0-8), per-criterion verdicts, suggested fixes, and applicable waivers.

- **TRIAGE MODE**: Classifies attempt outcomes post-execution (already_satisfied, no_changes_unverified, needs_investigation, blocked, timeout, tests_red, merge_conflict, etc.). Returns classification, recommended_action, rationale, and suggested_followup_beads.

- **REFINE MODE**: Advisory YAML/JSON diff for operator-invoked bead amendments. Covers title, description sections, acceptance criteria, labels, parent, deps, and notes.

- **WAIVER TABLE**: Allows criterion skips for doc-only beads (criteria c,d), epic beads (specific test parts, concrete implementation), and deletion/rename beads (criterion d).

All modes ground scoring in `docs/helix/06-iterate/bead-authoring-template.md` and emphasize prompt-only implementation for stable agent contracts.

### 2. `/var/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-b14c4924-20260507T231026-9169c6ef/skills/ddx/SKILL.md`

The root DDx skill definition. Establishes DDx (Document-Driven Development eXperience) as a CLI platform with:

- **Core concepts**: beads (work items), queue, ready/blocked status, claim/close lifecycle, try/work execution, runs, agents, harnesses, personas, roles, bindings, power bounds, plugins, skills, subagents, updates, upgrades, review (bead and adversarial), governing artifacts, and spec-ids.

- **Intent router**: Directs users to reference files based on intent:
  - `reference/beads.md` for bead metadata and AC
  - `reference/work.md` for queue execution
  - `reference/review.md` for bead/code review
  - `bead-lifecycle/` for readiness, scoring, triage, refine
  - `reference/agents.md` for harness/model/persona
  - `reference/status.md` for queue health

- **Top-level policies**: never edit `.ddx/beads.jsonl` directly, commit tracker changes, preserve attempt commit history, use worktrees for parallel agents, default to power-first dispatch.

Emphasizes that the skill is an overview + router; real domain guidance lives in reference files.

### 3. `/var/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-b14c4924-20260507T231026-9169c6ef/docs/helix/02-design/adr/ADR-023-bead-lifecycle-quality-policy.md`

ADR-023 (Proposed/Accepted) establishes bead-lifecycle quality enforcement as policy. Key decisions:

- **Two checkpoints**: bead readiness assessment (before claim/dispatch, evaluates tractability via canonical 8-criterion rubric) and post-attempt triage (classifies outcomes).

- **Staged rollout**: WARN-ONLY (default, reports score and proceeds) → BLOCK mode (opt-in, stops dispatch on low score) → factory mode (BLOCK + adversarial review).

- **Waiver model**: Rubric-level skips for doc-only/epic/deletion/rename beads, plus per-bead `lint-waiver:<criterion>` labels. Operator override uses `--force --reason`.

- **Fail-open**: Infra failures record and proceed in WARN-ONLY; BLOCK mode respects only valid post-waiver scores below threshold. Post-attempt triage failures never erase results.

- **Safe improvement**: Readiness may normalize description, add file:line evidence, add obvious test commands, wire labels/parent/deps. Must block for human input on scope changes, conflicting requirements, or guesses.

- **Decomposition**: Parent bead may decompose to children before claim, with every parent AC mapping to at least one child AC.

**Consequences**: FEAT-004 owns label-based waivers; FEAT-010 owns hook insertion and attempt classification; FEAT-011 owns nested workflow-skill packaging. Legacy beads run in WARN-ONLY while queue is baselined; BLOCK mode is opt-in until baseline confirms ordinary beads consistently satisfy the rubric.

### 4. `/var/tmp/ddx-exec-wt/.execute-bead-wt-ddx-b14c4924-20260507T231026-9169c6ef/cli/internal/agent/preclaim_intake_hook.go` (lines 160–200)

This Go function constructs the JSON prompt envelope for bead readiness assessment:

```go
func buildPreClaimIntakePrompt(projectRoot string, store BeadReader, b *bead.Bead) (string, error) {
	env := preClaimIntakePromptEnvelope{
		Title:         strings.TrimSpace(b.Title),
		Description:   strings.TrimSpace(b.Description),
		Acceptance:    strings.TrimSpace(b.Acceptance),
		Labels:        append([]string(nil), b.Labels...),
		PriorAttempts: []preClaimIntakeAttempt{},
		Depth:         beadDecompositionDepth(projectRoot, b),
		Parent:        strings.TrimSpace(b.Parent),
		Dependencies:  append([]string(nil), b.DepIDs()...),
	}

	// Prior attempts are optional for the gate. If bead history is available,
	// include the last few attempt/result summaries to help the classifier
	// distinguish a first-pass atomic bead from repeated decomposition.
	if store != nil {
		if eventStore, ok := any(store).(interface {
			Events(id string) ([]bead.BeadEvent, error)
		}); ok {
			if events, err := eventStore.Events(b.ID); err == nil && len(events) > 0 {
				for i := len(events) - 1; i >= 0 && len(env.PriorAttempts) < 5; i-- {
					ev := events[i]
					if ev.Kind != "bead.result" && ev.Kind != "execute-bead" {
						continue
					}
					env.PriorAttempts = append(env.PriorAttempts, preClaimIntakeAttempt{
						Status:    strings.TrimSpace(ev.Summary),
						Rationale: strings.TrimSpace(ev.Body),
					})
				}
			}
		}
	}

	body, err := json.MarshalIndent(env, "", "  ")
	if err != nil {
		return "", err
	}

	var sb strings.Builder
	sb.WriteString("MODE: intake\n")
```

The function populates a prompt envelope with bead metadata (title, description, acceptance criteria, labels, parent, dependencies), bead decomposition depth, and up to 5 prior attempt summaries filtered from the event store. It then marshals the envelope to indented JSON and begins building a string that starts with `"MODE: intake\n"` (implementing the intake mode contract from the bead-lifecycle skill).

